title: Multiple-Ascending Dose, Safety, Tolerability, Pharmacokinetic, and Pharmacodynamic Study of LY2886721 in Healthy Subjects
description_brief: This is a Phase 1 study in healthy subjects to evaluate the safety and tolerability of LY2886721 multiple doses, how the body handles the drug, and the drug's effect on the body.

outcomeMeasures.title: Number of Participants With Clinically Significant Effects
outcomeMeasures.description: Clinically significant effects were defined as serious and nonserious adverse events. A summary of serious and all other nonserious adverse events is located in the Reported Adverse Event module. The number of participants with at least 1 adverse event in each treatment arm is reported for this outcome measure.

drug: LY2886721 (oral small-molecule BACE1 / beta‑secretase inhibitor; developed by Eli Lilly)
explanation_target: Reason: The investigational product LY2886721 is an oral small‑molecule inhibitor of BACE1 (beta‑secretase) designed to reduce production of amyloid‑β (Aβ) — i.e., it targets Alzheimer’s pathological mechanism rather than purely symptomatic cognition or neuropsychiatric features. citeturn0search2turn0search6

Act (trial & PD effects extracted): The trial title and description correspond to a Phase 1 multiple‑ascending dose safety/tolerability/PK/PD study in healthy subjects (multiple‑dose MAD design). The study measured pharmacokinetics and pharmacodynamic biomarkers (plasma and CSF Aβ species), and LY2886721 produced dose‑dependent lowering of CSF and plasma Aβ in humans. citeturn1search6turn1search0

Act (drug development/status): LY2886721 was developed by Eli Lilly, advanced through Phase 1 (and into Phase 2), but Lilly voluntarily terminated a Phase 2 study because some subjects developed abnormal liver biochemistry. This is consistent with LY2886721 being a small‑molecule BACE inhibitor (not a biologic). citeturn0search3turn0search5

Reflect (classification justification): Because LY2886721 is a small‑molecule inhibitor of an Alzheimer’s disease enzyme (BACE1) intended to lower amyloid production (a disease‑modifying mechanism), the correct category is 'disease‑targeted small molecule' rather than a biologic, cognitive enhancer, or symptom management agent. There is no indication in the description that the trial is diagnostic or non‑therapeutic, so 'N/A' is not appropriate. citeturn0search2turn0search6

Web search results / key sources consulted: PubMed article describing LY2886721 as a potent/selective BACE1 inhibitor with robust Aβ lowering in animals and humans. citeturn0search2; Eli Lilly press release announcing voluntary termination of Phase II due to abnormal liver biochemical tests. citeturn0search3; Selleck/compound datasheet and NCATS entries describing LY2886721 as an oral small‑molecule BACE inhibitor. citeturn0search6turn0search0; Phase 1 study records/abstracts (multiple ascending dose, PK/PD in healthy volunteers) and clinical trial registry entries for the MAD Phase 1 study. citeturn1search0turn1search6
explanation_agent: Reason: The investigational drug LY2886721 is an oral small‑molecule inhibitor of BACE1 (β‑secretase), an enzyme that initiates production of amyloid‑β (Aβ); the mechanism explicitly aims to lower Aβ production (disease‑modifying, not purely symptomatic). citeturn0search1turn0search4

Act: Extracted trial details — drug: LY2886721 (oral small‑molecule BACE1 inhibitor); study: multiple‑ascending dose PK/PD in healthy subjects with dose‑dependent lowering of plasma and CSF Aβ species; development note: Lilly terminated a Phase II study because of abnormal liver biochemistry. These findings establish the intervention’s direct action on the amyloid pathway. citeturn0search1turn0search0

Reflect: Classification justification — LY2886721 targets BACE1 to reduce Aβ generation, which maps directly to CADRO category A) Amyloid beta. The intervention is a single, disease‑targeted small molecule acting on the amyloid production pathway (not a multi‑target agent, diagnostic, or symptomatic therapy), so A) Amyloid beta is the most specific and appropriate CADRO assignment. citeturn0search1turn0search4
